{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2018}} {{Infobox person | name = Ilana Löwy | image = | caption = | birth_name = Ilana Zelmanowicz | birth_date = 1948 | birth_place = [[Poland]] | death_date = | death_place = | residence = France | nationality = France | occupation = historian of life sciences, feminist scholar | employer = CERMES-3 ([[Inserm]]-[[CNRS]]-[[School for Advanced Studies in the Social Sciences|EHESS]]) | alma_mater = [[Tel Aviv University]], [[Paris Diderot University]] | awards = | spouse = | children = }}
'''Ilana Löwy''' (née '''Zelmanowicz'''), born in 1948 in [[Łódź]], [[Poland]], is a historian of biomedical sciences and a feminist. She works as a research director at an interdisciplinary and cross-institutional research unit CERMES-3 (''Centre de recherche médecine, sciences, santé, santé mentale, société'', [[Inserm]]-[[CNRS]]-[[School for Advanced Studies in the Social Sciences|EHESS]]),<ref name=cermes3>[http://www.cermes3.cnrs.fr/fr/membres/168-lowy-ilana Personal page] at the www.cermes3.cnrs.fr</ref> and is associated with the Department of Global Health and Social Medicine at [[King's College London]],<ref>[https://www.kcl.ac.uk/sspp/departments/sshm/people/Visiting-Professors/ilanalowy.aspx www.kcl.ac.uk]</ref> the Department of the History of Science at [[Harvard University]]<ref>[https://histsci.fas.harvard.edu/people/associates histsci.fas.harvard.edu]</ref> and [[Oswaldo Cruz Foundation|Casa de Oswaldo Cruz]], [[Fiocruz]], Rio de Janeiro.<ref>[http://www.ppghcs.coc.fiocruz.br/index.php/en/faculty ppghcs.coc.fiocruz.br]</ref>
==Biography== Born in a Jewish family in Poland, her parents decided to leave for Israel in 1957. She gained her [[Master of Science|Msc]] in [[microbiology]] and [[biochemistry]] from [[Tel Aviv University]] in 1971, and her PhD (''Doctorat D'Etat es Sciences'') from [[Paris Diderot University|Paris VII University]] in 1977.<ref>[http://www.sudoc.abes.fr/DB=2.1/SRCH?IKT=12&TRM=160949645 sudoc.abes.fr]</ref>
==Career== At the beginning of her career, Ilana Löwy was a working at the [[Institut Pasteur]] at the [[immunology|Cellular immunity]] lab. Her interest for the history of science initially evolved around the history of organ transplantation, bacteriology, immunology, virology and tropical medicine. With an increasing interest for human reproduction and cancer, her works associate now an extensive analysis of biomedical analysis and a reflexion [[gender studies|on gender]]. She has extensively published on [[Ludwik Fleck]], Polish historian and [[Philosophy of medicine|philosopher of medicine]]. Her current (2017) research focuses on [[prenatal diagnosis]], [[genetics]] and [[congenital disorder]]s.<ref name=cermes3 />
